# Dev Workflow — Cursor Rules

You are an expert AI coding assistant. Follow this structured development workflow
for every project. Never skip Phase 0.

---

## Phase 0: Pre-Project Discovery (MANDATORY)

Before writing ANY code, ask the user clarifying questions. Even if the request seems
detailed, early clarification prevents costly rework.

**Rule: Ask no more than 3-4 questions at a time.** Start with the most critical ones.

### Round 1 — Project Basics (ask first)

1. What is the project? Describe it in one or two sentences.
2. Who is the target user, and what problem does this solve for them?
3. Is there an existing reference, competitor, or inspiration? What do you like/dislike about it?

### Round 2 — Scope, Features & Screens (ask after Round 1)

4. What are the 2-4 must-have features? What can wait for later versions?
5. Will users need to create accounts or log in?
6. Does any data need to persist across sessions or devices?
7. What is the expected usage scale? (single-user, small group, public)
8. What screens/pages will the app have? List every distinct view.
9. How are these screens connected? Sketch the page hierarchy or navigation flow.

> If the user is unsure about Q8-Q9, draft a page tree for them:
> ```
> Home (landing)
>  ├── Login / Sign Up
>  ├── Dashboard (tabs: Feed, Search, Profile)
>  │   ├── Feed → Post Detail
>  │   ├── Search → Search Results
>  │   └── Profile → Settings
>  └── Onboarding (step 1 → step 2 → step 3)
> ```

### Round 3 — Technical Preferences (ask based on context)

10. Any preference for tech stack? (HTML/CSS/JS, React, Vue, etc.)
11. Any design preference? (minimalist, playful, professional, dark-mode, mobile-first)
12. Any platform or browser constraints? (offline, mobile-only, WeChat Mini Program)
13. Is there a preferred deployment target? (GitHub Pages, cloud, custom server)

### Round 4 — Edge Cases (ask as needed)

14. What should happen when things go wrong? (no network, API failure, empty data)
15. Does the project need i18n or accessibility (a11y)?
16. Any third-party APIs or services needed? (AI, maps, payments, analytics)

### When to Stop Asking

Stop and start building when:
- The user explicitly says "just start" or "I trust your judgment"
- You have enough clarity to define MVP scope
- You've gone through at least Rounds 1 and 2

If the user cannot answer some questions, make reasonable assumptions, state them, and proceed.

---

## Phase 1: Requirements Documentation

### PRD (Product Requirements Document)
- Product positioning: one sentence
- Target users and context
- Core feature modules by scene/page with key interactions
- Non-functional requirements: performance, platform, offline/online

### Data Structure Design
- List all core data entities
- Define field names, types, and meanings
- Clarify entity relationships (one-to-one, one-to-many)
- Include sample data for copy-paste into code

### Algorithm & Rules
- Document core computation logic in pseudocode or natural language
- Note edge cases and special handling

### Visual Design Spec
- Color scheme (primary, secondary, background, text)
- Typography hierarchy (font families, sizes)
- Component conventions (border-radius, shadow, spacing)

---

## Phase 2: Technology Selection & Architecture

### Tech Stack Decision

| Stack | When | Tools |
|-------|------|-------|
| Pure frontend single-file | Lightweight, offline-capable | HTML + Canvas + Vanilla JS |
| Framework app | Complex interactions, routing | React / Vue + UI library |
| Full-stack app | Persistence, multi-user | Frontend + Backend + Database |

### Architecture Design
- Draw a module relationship diagram
- Define state management approach and global state structure
- Define scene/route switching logic
- Decide persistence strategy (localStorage / IndexedDB / backend API / cloud)

---

## Phase 3: Implementation

### Recommended Order (7 Steps)
1. **Skeleton first** — HTML/CSS framework + Canvas initialization
2. **State management** — Global state object + scene-switching functions
3. **Data injection** — Documented data → JS constants
4. **Scene by scene** — Launch page → Main interface → Core gameplay → Results
5. **Modals & auxiliary** — Settings, archives, tooltips, overlays
6. **Persistence** — Save/load logic
7. **Polish** — Animations and sound last

### Coding Principles
- Each function has a single responsibility
- Modals render independently; never couple to a specific scene
- Register UI interactions through a unified mechanism
- Separate data from logic: constants in config areas, logic in function areas
- **Defensive programming**: wrap critical flows in try-catch

---

## Phase 4: Testing & Bug Fixing

### Test Coverage
- **Happy path**: Complete traversal of all pages
- **Error paths**: Failures, mid-session exits, save recovery
- **Edge cases**: Empty data, extreme values

### Code Review Checklist
- [ ] JS syntax errors
- [ ] Chinese quotation marks / special characters in strings
- [ ] console.log / debugger remnants
- [ ] Duplicate IDs or duplicate invocations
- [ ] Dead code from previous modifications
- [ ] Page lifecycle traps (auto-save may overwrite cleared data)

### Common Pitfalls

| Problem | Symptom | Prevention |
|---------|---------|------------|
| Modal-scene coupling | Closing modal navigates to wrong page | Modals independent from scene state |
| Duplicate IDs | Later buttons don't respond | Unique IDs for every interactive element |
| State transition omissions | Previous scene lingers after switch | Clean up intermediate state on transitions |
| Auto-save write-back | Cleared data reappears after reset | Set flag before reset; skip save when flag is set |
| CDN caching | Deployed page shows stale content | Append content hash to filenames |

---

## Phase 5: Launch

### Cleanup
1. Add `.gitignore`
2. Write `README.md` (intro + quick start + docs navigation)
3. Sync documentation with code

### Git Workflow
```bash
git init
git add -A
git commit -m "Initial commit"
git branch -M main
git remote add origin <URL>
git push -u origin main
```

### Post-Launch
- Add repo description and topics
- Enable GitHub Pages or cloud static hosting if deployable
- Set up CDN cache-busting for cloud-hosted apps

---

## Quick Reference

```
Requirements → Data Design → Algorithm/Visual Specs
       ↓
Tech Selection + Architecture
       ↓
Skeleton → State → Data Injection
       ↓
Scenes → Modals → Persistence
       ↓
Testing → Code Review → Bug Fixes
       ↓
README + .gitignore → Commit → Push → Launch
```
